org.biolegato.tables

Class CSVFile

  • java.lang.Object
    • javax.swing.filechooser.FileFilter
      • org.biolegato.tables.CSVFile
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    CSVFileConstants

    public class CSVFile
extends javax.swing.filechooser.FileFilter
implements CSVFileConstants

    CSV (Comma Separated Values) file format parser. A CSV file is a spreadsheet, where the rows are separated by new line characters (i.e. each line of the file is a row), and the columns are separated by comma characters. Thus an example of a CSV file would be:

           Name,Phone Num,Birthday
       John,555-5123,Apr. 30, 1937
       Jane,555-4352,Feb. 13, 1976
       Sam,555-6333,Jan. 7, 1961
       Tom,555-7777,Aug. 4, 1943

    Where name, phone number, and birthday are all separated by comma characters and are each columns of a spreadsheet.

    NOTE: fields may be double or single quoted. In such cases, the single or double quotes character may be escaped by doubling it (e.g. "AB""C" will be read as AB"C).

    Author:
    Graham Alvare, Brian Fristensky

      • readCSV

        public static java.lang.String[][] readCSV(java.io.Reader currentFile)
                                    throws java.io.IOException
        Reads CSV data from a Reader object into a 2D string array. Please note that the 2D string array is specified as follows: the rows are the first index of the array (e.g. data[0] is the first row of the array), and the columns are the second index of the array (e.g. data[0][1] is the second column of the first row of the array.
        Parameters:
        currentFile - the Reader object to parsed the CSV data from.
        Throws:
        java.io.IOException - thrown if there is any exception while reading from the Reader object.

      • writeFile

        public static void writeFile(java.lang.Appendable writer,
                             java.lang.String[][] data)
                      throws java.io.IOException
        Writes a 2D string array as CSV data into an Appendable object. Please note that the rows are the first index of the array (e.g. data[0] is the first row of the array), and the columns are the second index of the array (e.g. data[0][1] is the second column of the first row of the array.
        Parameters:
        writer - the Appendable object to write the CSV data to.
        data - the 2D string array to parse into CSV data.
        Throws:
        java.io.IOException - thrown if there is any exception while writing to the Appendable object.
